**Promise vs Observable**

| | Promise | Observable |
|---|---|---|
| **Values** | Single value (or error) | Stream of 0..N values over time |
| **Eagerness** | **Eager** — executes immediately on creation | **Lazy** — executes only when subscribed |
| **Cancellation** | Not natively cancellable | Unsubscribe cancels execution |
| **Multicast** | Always shared — one resolution, many `.then()` handlers get same value | **Unicast** by default — each subscription triggers independent execution (can multicast via operators) |
| **Built-in?** | Yes — native JS (`ES2015+`) | No — requires a library (RxJS, most commonly) |
| **Retry** | Manual re-invocation | Built-in operators (`retry`, `retryWhen`) |
| **Operators** | `.then()`, `.catch()`, `.finally()` | Massive operator library (`map`, `filter`, `switchMap`, `debounceTime`, `combineLatest`, …) |

**Key mental model:**

- **Promise** = a single async result. Think: one HTTP response, one timeout.
- **Observable** = an async stream. Think: WebSocket messages, user clicks, polling intervals.

**Quick examples:**

```js
// Promise — single value, eager
const p = new Promise(resolve => {
  console.log('runs immediately');
  resolve(42);
});
p.then(v => console.log(v)); // 42

// Observable (RxJS) — stream, lazy
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';
const o = new Observable(subscriber => {
  console.log('runs on subscribe');
  subscriber.next(1);
  subscriber.next(2);
  subscriber.complete();
});
o.subscribe(v => console.log(v)); // 1, 2
```

**When to use which:**

- **Promise** → one-shot async ops (fetch, file read, DB query)
- **Observable** → event streams, real-time data, complex async composition (cancellation, debounce, combining multiple sources)

Promises can be converted to Observables (`from(promise)`) and vice versa (`.toPromise()` / `firstValueFrom()`), so they interop cleanly.

